ef="https://encyclopediavirginia.org/media/">Media</a></li><li id="menu-item-96987" class="menu-item menu-item-type-custom menu-item-object-custom menu-item-96987"><a href="https://encyclopediavirginia.org/media/?type=virtual-tour">Virtual Tours</a></li><li id="menu-item-96988" class="menu-item menu-item-type-custom menu-item-object-custom menu-item-96988"><a href="https://www.givecampus.com/campaigns/30617/donations/new?a=5765859">Donate</a></li></ul></div></div></nav><!-- #site-navigation --><div class="searchandsocial"><form role="search" method="get" class="search-form" action="https://encyclopediavirginia.org/"> <label> <span class="screen-reader-text">Search:</span> <input type="search" class="search-field" placeholder="Search…" value="" name="s"> </label> <input type="image" src="https://encyclopediavirginia.org/wp-content/themes/ev/img/magnifyingglass.svg" class="search-submit" alt="Search"></form> <a class="social" href="https://www.facebook.com/encyclopediava"><img src="https://encyclopediavirginia.org/wp-content/themes/ev/img/square-facebook.svg" alt="Facebook" width="27" height="27"></a> <a class="social" href="http://www.twitter.com/encyclopediaVA"><img src="https://encyclopediavirginia.org/wp-content/themes/ev/img/square-x-twitter.svg" alt="Twitter" width="27" height="27"></a> <a class="social" href="https://www.instagram.com/encyclopediavirginia/"><img src="https://encyclopediavirginia.org/wp-content/themes/ev/img/square-instagram.svg" alt="Instagram" width="27" height="27"></a></div></header><!-- #masthead --></div><div id="content" class="site-content"><div id="primary" class="content-area"><main id="main" class="site-main"><article id="post-128472" class="entry post-128472 entries type-entries status-publish hentry category-african-american-history category-colonial-history-ca-1560-1763 category-slavery"><div class="headerwrapper"><div class="entry-banner"><div class="msg-banner"></div></div><header class="entry-header portraitright"><div class="summary-illustration"></div><div class="toplbl label">ENTRY</div><h1 class="entry-title">Angela (fl. 1619–1625)</h1><div class="evsummary"><div class="label">SUMMARY</div><p class="summary">Angela (also Angelo) was an enslaved laborer and among the <span class="replacedlink"><a href="https://encyclopediavirginia.org/entries/africans-virginias-first/">first Africans</a></span> to arrive in the <span class="replacedlink"><a href="https://encyclopediavirginia.org/entries/colonial-virginia/">Virginia colony</a></span> in 1619. She appears in the census of 1624 as “Angela a Negar” and the next year as “Angelo a Negro Woman in the <em>Treasurer</em>.” Likely born in present-day Angola, Angela was one of 350 African men and women captured by Portuguese raiders and their African allies in 1619 and <span class="replacedlink"><a href="https://encyclopediavirginia.org/entries/transatlantic-slave-trade-the/">sold to a Portuguese slave trader</a></span>. On the way to America, however, two English ships, the <em>White Lion</em> and the <em>Treasurer</em>, attacked the slave ship and stole about fifty of its Africans, sailing them to Virginia. There Captain <span class="replacedlink"><a href="https://encyclopediavirginia.org/entries/peirce-william-d-btw-1645-and-1647/">William Peirce</a></span> likely purchased Angela. By 1625, having survived the violence of Africa and the <span class="replacedlink"><a href="https://encyclopediavirginia.org/entries/slave-ships-and-the-middle-passage/">Middle Passage</a></span>, disease in Virginia, and a <span class="replacedlink"><a href="https://encyclopediavirginia.org/entries/anglo-powhatan-war-second-1622-1632/">deadly attack</a></span> by <span class="replacedlink"><a href="https://encyclopediavirginia.org/entries/indians-in-virginia/">Virginia Indians</a></span>, she was living in his household with Mrs. Peirce and three white <span class="replacedlink"><a href="https://encyclopediavirginia.org/entries/indentured-servants-in-colonial-virginia/">indentured servants</a></span>. Little else is known of Angela’s life, although archaeologists excavating the Peirce residence in 2017 and 2018 have discovered at least one artifact, a cowrie shell, they believe may have been connected to her labor there. Her date of death is unknown.</p></div><nav id="pagenav"></nav></header><!-- .entry-header --></div><div class="maincontent"><div class="label">READING LEVEL</div> <a href="#Grade8" class="rlinput rlheader" id="Grade8">Grade 8</a><div class="rlcontent"><p>Angela was an enslaved worker who first was <a href="https://encyclopediavirginia.org/entries/africans-virginias-first/">brought to the Virginia colony in 1619</a>. She was probably born in present-day Angola. Angela was one of 350 men and women who were captured by <a href="https://encyclopediavirginia.org/entries/transatlantic-slave-trade-the/">Portuguese slave traders</a>. The ship that Angela was on was attacked by two English ships. The English stole about 50 Africans who were on board and sailed them to Virginia. Angela survived the <a href="https://encyclopediavirginia.org/entries/slave-ships-and-the-middle-passage/">Middle Passage</a>, disease in Virginia, and a <a href="https://encyclopediavirginia.org/entries/anglo-powhatan-war-second-1622-1632/">deadly attack</a> by <a href="https://encyclopediavirginia.org/entries/indians-in-virginia/">Virginia Indians</a>. She lived in a household with <a href="https://encyclopediavirginia.org/entries/peirce-william-d-btw-1645-and-1647/">Captain William Pierce</a> and three white <a href="https://encyclopediavirginia.org/entries/indentured-servants-in-colonial-virginia/">indentured servants</a>. Very little is known about Angela’s life. But archaeologists continue to find evidence of her life at the original Pierce property.</p><h2><strong>In the Historical Record</strong></h2><p>Angela appears in the historical record twice, as part of censuses conducted in the Virginia colony in 1624 and 1625. She is listed as living with Captain William Pierce along with Pierce’s wife and three white indentured servants. One of 23 Africans in the colony, she is identified as “Angelo a Negro Woman in the <em>Treasurer</em>.” In later histories of <a href="https://encyclopediavirginia.org/entries/jamestown-settlement-early/">Jamestown</a> and she is referred to as both Angelo and Angela. Historians are unsure of why the censuses linked her with a traditionally male name. It could have been a mistake on the part of census takers, one repeated twice in a year. It may have been that her name was a version of <em>Angola</em>, Angela’s probable birthplace. The name also may have reflected an anglicization of her birth name.</p><h2><strong>Africa and the Middle Passage</strong></h2><div class="entry-image" data-attachid="78747"><div class="attachwrapper"><a href="https://encyclopediavirginia.org/1550-56b9d259d50b8ed/"><img width="640" height="896" src="https://encyclopediavirginia.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/11/1550_56b9d259d50b8ed.jpg" class="attachment-large size-large" alt="African king forges weapons and utensils over a fire while another figure uses a bellows in seventeenth-century West Africa" decoding="async" srcset="https://encyclopediavirginia.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/11/1550_56b9d259d50b8ed.jpg 714w, https://encyclopediavirginia.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/11/1550_56b9d259d50b8ed-214x300.jpg 214w" sizes="(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 640px" /></a><div class="imgcap"><a href="https://encyclopediavirginia.org/1550-56b9d259d50b8ed/">A West African King Forging Metal</a></div></div></div><p>The enslaved Africans aboard the <em>Treasurer</em> likely were Kimbundu-speaking people from a West African political region known as Ndongo. Part of present-day Angola, the region had long been unstable due to climate, political tensions, and the transatlantic slave trade. In 1575, the Portuguese military had come to a bay near the mouth of the Kwanza River in the hopes of finding silver. Portuguese attacks, along with a drought, left the people who survived vulnerable. In 1580 Portugal and Spain were united under the same crown. This opened Spain’s profitable Caribbean slave market to the Portuguese. As a result, the Portuguese and their African allies sometimes provoked violence for the purpose of capturing men and women and selling them to slave traders.</p><p>Angela likely had a rural upbringing in Ndongo, raising crops and tending cattle. Because of the Portuguese presence in the region, it is possible that she had had at least some contact with Christianity. She may even have been baptized, her name being evidence of this fact. The Portuguese required that slaves be baptized before they arrived in America. Angelia likely did not practice the religion at the time of her capture. Sometime in 1619 she was one of 350 enslaved Africans sold to the captain of the <em>São João Bautista.</em>  The Portuguese ship was bound for New Spain (present-day Mexico), where its human cargo would be sold as slaves. The vast majority would labor in the sugar plantations of the Caribbean and South America.</p><div class="entry-image" data-attachid="90476"><div class="attachwrapper"><a href="https://encyclopediavirginia.org/1548-382c7baec38ac7e/"><img width="640" height="529" src="https://encyclopediavirginia.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/11/1548_382c7baec38ac7e-1024x846.jpg" class="attachment-large size-large" alt="The landing of the first Negroes" decoding="async" srcset="https://encyclopediavirginia.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/11/1548_382c7baec38ac7e-1024x846.jpg 1024w, https://encyclopediavirginia.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/11/1548_382c7baec38ac7e-300x248.jpg 300w, https://encyclopediavirginia.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/11/1548_382c7baec38ac7e-768x634.jpg 768w, https://encyclopediavirginia.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/11/1548_382c7baec38ac7e-1536x1269.jpg 1536w, https://encyclopediavirginia.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/11/1548_382c7baec38ac7e-2048x1692.jpg 2048w, https://encyclopediavirginia.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/11/1548_382c7baec38ac7e-1200x991.jpg 1200w, https://encyclopediavirginia.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/11/1548_382c7baec38ac7e-1980x1636.jpg 1980w" sizes="(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 640px" /></a><div class="imgcap"><a href="https://encyclopediavirginia.org/1548-382c7baec38ac7e/"><em>The landing of the first Negroes</em></a></div></div></div><p>Somewhere in the Atlantic, the <em>São João Bautista</em> was attacked by two English ships, the <em>Treasurer</em> and <em>White Lion</em>. When it arrived in New Spain, the <em>São João Bautista</em> carried only 147 slaves, having lost 203 along the way. Many of these people likely died from disease. Others may have taken their own lives or been killed in the English ships’ attack. The remainder—between forty-five and fifty enslaved Africans—had been stolen by the <em>Treasurer</em> and <em>White Lion</em>. The two ships sailed for Virginia, and <em>White Lion</em> arriving at Point Comfort in August. <a href="https://encyclopediavirginia.org/entries/rolfe-john-d-1622/">John Rolfe</a>, the colony’s secretary, <a href="https://encyclopediavirginia.org/entries/twenty-and-odd-negroes-an-excerpt-from-a-letter-from-john-rolfe-to-sir-edwin-sandys-1619-1620/">noted</a> that it carried “20. and odd Negroes,” who were traded for food. Some, perhaps all, of the Africans were then transported to Jamestown and resold. The fact that these men and women were “bought” suggests to many historians that they were treated as slaves and not indentured servants.</p><p>The <em>Treasurer</em> arrived three or four days later and carried another 25-29 Africans. The captain later sold 14 enslaved people in Bermuda, suggesting that he had unloaded between 11 and 15 in Virginia. It is likely that Captain Peirce purchased at least one of these Africans, the woman Angela.</p><p><strong>In Virginia</strong></p><p>Angela’s age when she arrived in Virginia is unknown. But, already she had survived the violence of Portuguese and African slave hunters, the horrors of the Middle Passage, during which as much as 43 percent of <em>São João Bautista</em>‘s Africans had died, and the attack of the <em>Treasurer</em> and <em>White Lion</em>. In March 1620, a census counted thirty-two Africans in Virginia. Only twenty-one remained five years later, suggesting that Angela lived through the disease and illness that affected nearly all newcomers to the colony.</p><div class="attachwrapper"><div class="threedobject"> <iframe width="500" height="314" frameborder="0" scrolling="no" marginheight="0" marginwidth="0" src="https://sketchfab.com/models/4f915486f5684bb8a7064b4d09a884eb/embed" allowfullscreen=""></iframe><div class="capwrapper"> <a href="https://encyclopediavirginia.org/12496-2c45ca276a2ee1d/">Cowrie Shell</a></div></div></div><p>And on March 22, 1622, surprise attacks by Virginia Indians killed nearly a third of Virginia’s non-native population, an event that Angela also survived.</p><p>Little is known of Angela’s life in Virginia. Her owner, William Peirce, was captain of the Governor’s guard and commander of Jamestown Island. He was <a href="https://encyclopediavirginia.org/entries/elections-in-colonial-virginia/">elected</a> a <a href="https://encyclopediavirginia.org/entries/house-of-burgesses/">burgess</a> in 1624 and served on the <a href="https://encyclopediavirginia.org/entries/governors-council-the/">governor’s Council</a> from 1632 to 1643. Peirce ran a store in Jamestown and was heavily involved in the <a href="https://encyclopediavirginia.org/entries/tobacco-in-colonial-virginia/">tobacco</a> business initiated by his son-in-law John Rolfe. In 1625, the Peirce household included Mrs. Joane Peirce and the servants Thomas Smith, Henry Bradford, and Ester Edrife.</p></div> <a href="#Grade4" class="rlinput rlheader" id="Grade4">Grade 4</a><div class="rlcontent"><p>Angela was an enslaved worker in Virginia. She was <a href="https://encyclopediavirginia.org/entries/africans-virginias-first/">brought to the Virginia colony in 1619</a>. She was probably born in present-day Angola. Angela was one of 350 Africans who were captured by <a href="https://encyclopediavirginia.org/entries/transatlantic-slave-trade-the/">Portuguese slave traders</a>. The ship that Angela was on was attacked by two English ships. The English stole about 50 Africans who were on board. They were then sailed to Virginia. Angela survived the <a href="https://encyclopediavirginia.org/entries/slave-ships-and-the-middle-passage/">Middle Passage</a>, disease in Virginia, and a <a href="https://encyclopediavirginia.org/entries/anglo-powhatan-war-second-1622-1632/">deadly attack</a> by <a href="https://encyclopediavirginia.org/entries/indians-in-virginia/">Virginia Indians</a>. She lived in a household with <a href="https://encyclopediavirginia.org/entries/peirce-william-d-btw-1645-and-1647/">Captain William Pierce</a> and three white <a href="https://encyclopediavirginia.org/entries/indentured-servants-in-colonial-virginia/">indentured servants</a>. Very little is known about Angela’s life. But archaeologists continue to find evidence of her.</p><h2><strong>In the Historical Record</strong></h2><p>Details about Angela’s life can be found in records from the Virginia colony. She lived with Captain William Pierce and Pierce’s wife. Three white indentured servants also lived on the property. Angela was one of 23 Africans in the colony at that time. Records identify her as “Angelo a Negro Woman in the <em>Treasurer</em>.” In later records of <a href="https://encyclopediavirginia.org/entries/jamestown-settlement-early/">Jamestown</a>, she is called both Angelo and Angela. Historians are unsure of why she is described with a male name. It could have been a mistake. It may have been that her name was a version of <em>Angola. </em>Angola is the name of the place in Africa where she was probably born. The name also may show how her name was changed to sound more English.</p><h2><strong>Africa and the Middle Passage</strong></h2><div class="entry-image" data-attachid="78747"><div class="attachwrapper"><a href="https://encyclopediavirginia.org/1550-56b9d259d50b8ed/"><img width="640" height="896" src="https://encyclopediavirginia.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/11/1550_56b9d259d50b8ed.jpg" class="attachment-large size-large" alt="African king forges weapons and utensils over a fire while another figure uses a bellows in seventeenth-century West Africa" decoding="async" srcset="https://encyclopediavirginia.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/11/1550_56b9d259d50b8ed.jpg 714w, https://encyclopediavirginia.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/11/1550_56b9d259d50b8ed-214x300.jpg 214w" sizes="(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 640px" /></a><div class="imgcap"><a href="https://encyclopediavirginia.org/1550-56b9d259d50b8ed/">A West African King Forging Metal</a></div></div></div><p>The Africans arrived in Virginia on a ship called the <em>Treasurer. </em>They were probably from a region in West Africa called <em>Ndongo. </em>Portugal sent ships to Ndongo to capture Africans as slaves. The Portuguese sometimes worked with other African groups to capture people from Ndongo.</p><p>Angela likely had a rural lifestyle. People in Ndongo farmed crops and animals. The Portuguese made all enslaved people convert to the Christian religion. However, Angela probably did not practice the religion at the time that she was captured. In 1619, 350 Africans were captured. They were sold to a Portuguese slave trader. The slave trader put the Africans on a ship bound for New Spain (present-day Mexico). Most of the Africans would be enslaved on sugar plantations in South America.</p><p>The Portuguese slave ship was attacked by two English ships. The English ships were named the <em>Treasurer</em> and <em>White Lion. </em>The English ships captured the Africans who were on board. Many had died at some point on the voyage. The <em>White Lion </em>arrived at Point Comfort (Virginia) in August of 1619.<div class="entry-image" data-attachid="90476"><div class="attachwrapper"><a href="https://encyclopediavirginia.org/1548-382c7baec38ac7e/"><img width="640" height="529" src="https://encyclopediavirginia.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/11/1548_382c7baec38ac7e-1024x846.jpg" class="attachment-large size-large" alt="The landing of the first Negroes" decoding="async" srcset="https://encyclopediavirginia.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/11/1548_382c7baec38ac7e-1024x846.jpg 1024w, https://encyclopediavirginia.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/11/1548_382c7baec38ac7e-300x248.jpg 300w, https://encyclopediavirginia.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/11/1548_382c7baec38ac7e-768x634.jpg 768w, https://encyclopediavirginia.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/11/1548_382c7baec38ac7e-1536x1269.jpg 1536w, https://encyclopediavirginia.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/11/1548_382c7baec38ac7e-2048x1692.jpg 2048w, https://encyclopediavirginia.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/11/1548_382c7baec38ac7e-1200x991.jpg 1200w, https://encyclopediavirginia.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/11/1548_382c7baec38ac7e-1980x1636.jpg 1980w" sizes="(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 640px" /></a><div class="imgcap"><a href="https://encyclopediavirginia.org/1548-382c7baec38ac7e/"><em>The landing of the first Negroes</em></a></div></div></div> It carried “20. And odd Negroes” according to John Rolfe. These Africans were bought in exchange for food. The fact these men and women were bought gives historians a clue that they were treated mostly as slaves and not as indentured servants.</p><p>The <em>Treasurer</em> arrived three or four days later. It carried another 25-29 Africans. The captain later sold 14 enslaved people in Bermuda (an island off the coast of North America). He likely had sold between 11 and 15 Africans in Virginia. Captain Peirce purchased at least one of these Africans, the woman Angela.</p><h2><strong>In Virginia</strong></h2><p>In March 1620, a census counted 32 Africans in Virginia. Only 21 remained five years later. Many newcomers to the colony died of disease and sickness. On March 22, 1622, surprise attacks by Virginia Indians killed many colonists and Africans. Records show that Angela survived these near-death experiences.</p><p>Little is known of Angela’s life in Virginia. Her owner, William Peirce, was captain of the Governor’s guard and commander of Jamestown Island. He was <a href="https://encyclopediavirginia.org/entries/elections-in-colonial-virginia/">elected</a> a <a href="https://encyclopediavirginia.org/entries/house-of-burgesses/">burgess</a> in 1624. He also served on the <a href="https://encyclopediavirginia.org/entries/governors-council-the/">governor’s Council</a> from 1632 to 1643. Peirce owned a store in Jamestown and was involved in the <a href="https://encyclopediavirginia.org/entries/tobacco-in-colonial-virginia/">tobacco</a> business. In 1625, the Peirce household included Mrs. Joane Peirce, 3 white indentured servants, and Angela.</p><div class="attachwrapper"><div class="threedobject"> <iframe width="500" height="314" frameborder="0" scrolling="no" marginheight="0" marginwidth="0" src="https://sketchfab.com/models/4f915486f5684bb8a7064b4d09a884eb/embed" allowfullscreen=""></iframe><div class="capwrapper"> <a href="https://encyclopediavirginia.org/12496-2c45ca276a2ee1d/">Cowrie Shell</a></div></div></div><p>Angela may have cooked, cleaned, and helped care for the Peirces. In 2017 and 2018, archaeologists found at least one artifact on the Pierce property. A <em>cowrie</em> shell was found that may have belonged to Angela. Cowrie shells were common among the Africans in the colony. In 1635, Captain Peirce helped remove <a href="https://encyclopediavirginia.org/entries/harvey-sir-john-ca-1581-or-1582-by-1650/">Sir John Harvey</a> from the governor’s office. Harvey took back power two years later. In 1640 the king called Peirce to England. He was arrested and his property was seized. Eventually, his property was returned to him. It is unknown whether Angela was part of that list of property. Peirce returned to Virginia and died sometime between 1644 and 1647. The death date of Angela is unknown.</p></div> <a href="#original" id="original" class="rlinput rlheader rloriginal">Grades 11+</a><div class="entry-meta"> <span class="byline"> Contributor: <span class="author vcard"><a class="url fn n" href="https://encyclopediavirginia.org/author/brendanwolfe/">Brendan Wolfe</a></span></span><div class="byline"><ul></ul></div></div><!-- .entry-meta --> <!--<div class="label">FULL ENTRY</div>--><div class="entry-content"><div class="entry"><div class="section"><h2>In the Historical Record</h2><p><img decoding="async" class="lazyload" src="data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAAAAAAP///yH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAIBRAA7" data-src="evr2129" /><noscript><img decoding="async" class="lazyload" src="evr2129" /></noscript>Angela appears in the historical record just twice, as part of censuses conducted in the Virginia colony on February 16, 1624, and January 24, 1625. In the first she is one of the colony&#8217;s twenty-one Africans, identified as &#8220;Angela a Negar&#8221; and living in James City. The second muster provides more detail, grouping residents according to household and including, when possible, their ages. In this list she is located in the James City household of Captain William Peirce, with Peirce&#8217;s wife and three presumably white indentured servants. One of twenty-three Africans in the colony, she is identified this time as &#8220;Angelo a Negro Woman in the <em>Treasurer</em>.&#8221; In subsequent histories of <span class="replacedlink"><a href="https://encyclopediavirginia.org/entries/jamestown-settlement-early/">Jamestown</a></span> and early Virginia she is referred to as both Angelo and Angela, and historians are unsure of why the census associated her with a traditionally male name. It could have been a mistake on the part of census takers, or it may have been that her name was a corruption of Angola, Angela&#8217;s likely birthplace. The name also may have reflected an anglicization of her birth name.</p></div><div class="section"><h2>Africa and the Middle Passage</h2><div class="entry-image" data-attachid="78747"><img decoding="async" class="attachment-large size-large lazyload" src="data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAAAAAAP///yH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAIBRAA7" data-src="https://encyclopediavirginia.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/11/1550_56b9d259d50b8ed.jpg" alt="Life in Seventeenth-Century Africa" width="640" height="896" /><noscript><img decoding="async" class="attachment-large size-large lazyload" src="https://encyclopediavirginia.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/11/1550_56b9d259d50b8ed.jpg" alt="Life in Seventeenth-Century Africa" width="640" height="896" /></noscript></p><div class="imgcap"><a href="https://encyclopediavirginia.org/1550_56b9d259d50b8ed/">Life in Seventeenth-Century Africa</a></div></div><p>Angela and her fellow enslaved Africans aboard the <em>Treasurer</em> likely were Kimbundu-speaking people from a West African polity known as Ndongo. Part of present-day Angola, the region had long been unstable as a result of climate, geopolitics, and the economy of the transatlantic slave trade. In 1575, the Portuguese military had entered a bay near the mouth of the Kwanza River in the hopes of eventually finding silver in the interior. Subsequent Portuguese raids, along with a drought that dispersed communities in search of food, left the people who remained particularly vulnerable. In 1580 Portugal and Spain were united under the same crown, opening Spain&#8217;s lucrative Caribbean slave market to the Portuguese. As a result, the Portuguese and their African allies sometimes provoked violence for the purpose of capturing men and women, such as those in Ndongo, and selling them to slave traders.</p><p>Angela likely had a rural upbringing in Ndongo, raising crops such as millet and sorghum and tending cattle. It is possible, because of the Portuguese presence in the region, that she had had at least some contact with Christianity. She may even have been baptized, her name being evidence of this fact. The Portuguese required that slaves be baptized before they arrived in America, but it was generally a pro forma gesture. Angelia likely did not practice the religion at the time of her capture. Sometime in 1619 she was one of 350 enslaved Africans sold to Manuel Mendes da Cunha, captain of the the <em>São João Bautista</em> at the port of São Paulo de Luando. The Portuguese ship was bound for Vera Cruz, New Spain (present-day Mexico), where its human cargo would be sold as slaves, with the vast majority going to labor in the sugar plantations of the Caribbean and South America.</p><div class="entry-image" data-attachid="90476"><img decoding="async" class="attachment-large size-large lazyload" src="data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAAAAAAP///yH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAIBRAA7" data-src="https://encyclopediavirginia.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/11/1548_382c7baec38ac7e-1024x846.jpg" alt="The landing of the first Negroes" width="640" height="529" /><noscript><img decoding="async" class="attachment-large size-large lazyload" src="https://encyclopediavirginia.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/11/1548_382c7baec38ac7e-1024x846.jpg" alt="The landing of the first Negroes" width="640" height="529" /></noscript></p><div class="imgcap"><a href="https://encyclopediavirginia.org/1548_382c7baec38ac7e/">The landing of the first Negroes</a></div></div><p>Somewhere in the Atlantic, however, the <em>São João Bautista</em> was attacked by two English ships, the <em>Treasurer</em> and <em>White Lion</em>. They were sailing with letters of marque, which provided official sanction from foreign governments to prey on Spanish and Portuguese ships, stealing valuable cargo. When it arrived in Vera Cruz, the <em>São João Bautista</em> carried only 147 slaves, having lost 203 along the way. Many of these people likely died from disease; others may have taken their own lives or been killed in the English ships&#8217; attack. The remainder—between forty-five and fifty enslaved Africans—had been stolen by the <em>Treasurer</em> and <em>White Lion</em>. The two ships promptly sailed for Virginia, with the <em>White Lion</em> arriving at Point Comfort sometime late in August. <span class="replacedlink"><a href="https://encyclopediavirginia.org/entries/rolfe-john-d-1622/">John Rolfe</a></span>, the colony&#8217;s secretary, <span class="replacedlink"><a href="https://encyclopediavirginia.org/entries/twenty-and-odd-negroes-an-excerpt-from-a-letter-from-john-rolfe-to-sir-edwin-sandys-1619-1620/">noted</a></span> that it carried &#8220;20. and odd Negroes,&#8221; who were &#8220;bought for victualle [food] … at the best and easyest rate they could.&#8221; Some, perhaps all, of the Africans were then transported to Jamestown and resold. The fact that these men and women were &#8220;bought&#8221; suggests to many historians that they were treated as slaves and not indentured servants.</p><p>The <em>Treasurer</em> arrived three or four days later and carried another twenty-five to twenty-nine Africans. The colony&#8217;s deputy governor, <span class="replacedlink"><a href="https://encyclopediavirginia.org/entries/yeardley-sir-george-bap-1588-1627/">Sir George Yeardley</a></span>, sent Rolfe, Captain William Peirce, and another man to meet the ship, but by the time they arrived the <em>Treasurer</em> had fled. Because his letter of marque had expired, the captain feared arrest. He later sold fourteen slaves in Bermuda, suggesting that he had unloaded between eleven and fifteen in Virginia. (These numbers vary somewhat among historians.) It is likely that Peirce purchased at least one of these Africans, the woman Angela.</p></div><div class="section"><h2>In Virginia</h2><div class="entry-image" data-attachid="81827"><div class="imgcap"></div></div><p>Angela&#8217;s age when she arrived in Virginia is unknown, but already she had survived the violence of Portuguese and African slave hunters, the horrors of the Middle Passage, during which as much as 43 percent of <em>São João Bautista</em>&#8216;s Africans had died, and the attack of the <em>Treasurer</em> and <em>White Lion</em>. In March 1620, a muster counted thirty-two Africans in Virginia, but only twenty-one remained five years later, suggesting that Angela lived through the disease and illness that affected nearly all newcomers to the colony. And on March 22, 1622, coordinated surprise attacks by Virginia Indians killed nearly a third of Virginia&#8217;s non-native population, an event that Angela also survived.</p><p>Little is known of Angela&#8217;s life in Virginia. Her owner, William Peirce, was captain of the Governor&#8217;s guard and commander of Jamestown Island and its blockhouses, the small fortified structures that dotted the perimeter of the settlement. He was <span class="replacedlink"><a href="https://encyclopediavirginia.org/entries/elections-in-colonial-virginia/">elected</a></span> a <span class="replacedlink"><a href="https://encyclopediavirginia.org/entries/house-of-burgesses/">burgess</a></span> in 1624 and served on the <span class="replacedlink"><a href="https://encyclopediavirginia.org/entries/governors-council-the/">governor&#8217;s Council</a></span> from 1632 to 1643. A planter and entrepreneur, Peirce ran a store in Jamestown and was heavily involved in the <span class="replacedlink"><a href="https://encyclopediavirginia.org/entries/tobacco-in-colonial-virginia/">tobacco</a></span> business initiated by his son-in-law John Rolfe, who had been the first Virginian to cultivate a marketable form of the plant. In 1625, the Peirce household included Mrs. Joane Peirce and the servants Thomas Smith, aged seventeen, and Henry Bradford, aged thirty-five, both of whom had arrived aboard the <em>Abigaile</em> in January 1625. Ester Edrife worked as a <span class="replacedlink"><a href="https://encyclopediavirginia.org/entries/women-in-colonial-virginia/">maidservant</a></span> and had been in the colony since 1619 or 1620.</p><div class="entry-image" data-attachid="73791"><img decoding="async" class="attachment-large size-large lazyload" src="data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAAAAAAP///yH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAIBRAA7" data-src="https://encyclopediavirginia.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/11/12496_2c45ca276a2ee1d-1024x767.jpg" alt="Cowrie Shell" width="640" height="479" /><noscript><img decoding="async" class="attachment-large size-large lazyload" src="https://encyclopediavirginia.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/11/12496_2c45ca276a2ee1d-1024x767.jpg" alt="Cowrie Shell" width="640" height="479" /></noscript></p><div class="imgcap"><a href="https://encyclopediavirginia.org/12496_2c45ca276a2ee1d/">Cowrie Shell</a></div></div><p>Although Peirce patented land outside of James City on several occasions—for instance, 650 acres on Mulberry Island in December 1619—the 1625 muster indicates that Angela lived in an urban household. She may have cooked, cleaned, and in other ways helped care for the Peirces. In 2017 and 2018, archaeologists excavating the Peirce residence at Jamestown found at least one artifact, a cowrie shell, that has generally been associated with an African presence at other sites in Virginia and may be evidence of her labor. She was not among those laborers—six white men and one African man—who <span class="replacedlink"><a href="https://encyclopediavirginia.org/entries/runaway-slaves-and-servants-in-colonial-virginia/">attempted to escape</a></span> from Peirce on July 18, 1640. In 1635, Peirce played an important role in the ousting of <span class="replacedlink"><a href="https://encyclopediavirginia.org/entries/harvey-sir-john-ca-1581-or-1582-by-1650/">Sir John Harvey</a></span> from the governor&#8217;s office. Harvey regained power two years later, and in 1640 the king summoned Peirce to England, where he was detained and his personal estate seized but eventually returned. It is unknown whether Angela was part of that estate. Peirce returned to Virginia and died after 1644 but before June 22, 1647. The death date of Angela is unknown.</p></div></div></div><!-- .entry-content --></div><!-- .maincontent --><div class="externallinks"></div> <!--    Additional Media--><div id="maptrigger" class="relatedcontentw wrapper"><div class="innerwrap"><div class="label">RELATED CONTENT</div><div class="relatedcontent"><div class="related"><div class="relatedtitle">Categories:</div><ul class="taxlist"><li><a href="https://encyclopediavirginia.org/category/african-american-history/" rel="tag">African American History</a></li><li><a href="https://encyclopediavirginia.org/category/colonial-history-ca-1560-1763/" rel="tag">Colonial History (ca. 1560–1763)</a></li><li><a href="https://encyclopediavirginia.org/category/slavery/" rel="tag">Slavery</a></li></ul></div><div class="related"><div class="relatedtitle">Type:</div><ul class="taxlist"><li><a href="https://encyclopediavirginia.org/type/biography/" rel="tag">Biography</a></li></ul></div></div></div></div> <!--    Map--><div class="mapw wrapper" id="map"><div class="map"><div class="label">MAP</div><div id="place-map"> <!-- Map displays here --></div></div></div> <!--    Timeline--><div class="timelinew wrapper" id="timeline"><div class="timeline"><div class="label">TIMELINE</div><div class="chronitem"> <span class="date" id="chron0">1575 </span><div class="chrondescription">The Portuguese send a military expedition to the mouth of the Kwanza River in central Africa in search of silver.</div></div><div class="chronitem"> <span class="date" id="chron1">1580 </span><div class="chrondescription">The death of King Henry, of Portugal, leads to a dynastic union with Spain and Spanish access to Portugal's sources of slaves in Africa.</div></div><div class="chronitem"> <span class="date" id="chron2">1618—1619 </span><div class="chrondescription">Luis Mendes de Vasconçelos leads campaigns against Kimbundu-speaking people in West Central Africa, capturing thousands. These Africans likely provided the cargo for six slave ships that arrived in Mexico from June 1619 until June 1620.</div></div><div class="chronitem"> <span class="date" id="chron3">1619 </span><div class="chrondescription">Sometime in the first half of the year, the Portuguese slave ship <i>São João Bautista</i> leaves the port of São Paulo de Loanda, a Portuguese military outpost in West Africa, and sails for Vera Cruz, New Spain (present-day Mexico). It carries a cargo of 350 enslaved Africans.</div></div><div class="chronitem"> <span class="date" id="chron4">July—August 1619 </span><div class="chrondescription">Two English ships, the <i>White Lion</i> and the <i>Treasurer</i>, both sailing out of the Netherlands, intercept the Portuguese slaver <i>São João Bautista</i> off the coast of Campeche in present-day Yucatán. After stealing about sixty enslaved Africans, the ships sail to Virginia with the intention of selling them.</div></div><div class="chronitem hasgeo" data-long="-76.3113315" data-lat="37.0004248" data-date="Late August 1619" data-title="The ship White Lion arrives at Point Comfort and sells &#8220;20. and odd Negroes&#8221; in exchange for food." data-id="chron5"> <span class="date" id="chron5">Late August 1619 </span><div class="chrondescription">The <i>White Lion</i>, captained by John Colyn Jope, arrives at Point Comfort, where Jope sells "20. and odd Negroes" in exchange for food. These are the first Africans to enter the Virginia colony. Four days later, the <i>Treasurer</i> arrives and its captain, Daniel Elfrith, sells two or three of the enslaved Africans aboard.</div></div><div class="chronitem"> <span class="date" id="chron6">August 30, 1619 </span><div class="chrondescription">Manuel Mendes da Cunha, captain of the Portuguese slave ship <i>São João Bautista</i>, arrives in Vera Cruz, New Spain (present-day Mexico), with only 147 slaves. He left West Africa with 350, but some were stolen off the coast of Campeche and transported to Virginia for sale. Others probably died en route.</div></div><div class="chronitem"> <span class="date" id="chron7">March 1620 </span><div class="chrondescription">Virginia's first muster, or census, is compiled and lists 892 Europeans and, among "Others not Christians in the Service of the English," four Indians and thirty-two Africans. Fifteen of the Africans are male and seventeen are female.</div></div><div class="chronitem"> <span class="date" id="chron8">February 1624 </span><div class="chrondescription">The population of Europeans in the Virginia colony is 906. A muster, or census, lists twenty-one Africans, down from thirty-two in 1620. Twelve of the Africans are identified by name, suggesting they have been baptized.</div></div><div class="chronitem hasgeo" data-long="-76.783973" data-lat="37.224835" data-date="February 16, 1624" data-title="The Jamestown muster lists &#8220;Angelo a Negar&#8221; as living in the household of William Peirce." data-id="chron9"> <span class="date" id="chron9">February 16, 1624 </span><div class="chrondescription">The Jamestown muster lists "Angelo a Negar," an African woman, as living in the household of William Peirce.</div></div><div class="chronitem"> <span class="date" id="chron10">January 20—February 7, 1625 </span><div class="chrondescription">The population of Europeans in the Virginia colony is 1,232. A muster, or census, lists twenty-three Africans and one Indian, all of them servants. They live on plantations scattered from the mouth of the James River to Flowerdew Hundred.</div></div><div class="chronitem hasgeo" data-long="-76.783973" data-lat="37.224835" data-date="January 24, 1625" data-title="The Jamestown muster lists &#8220;Angelo a Negro Woman&#8221; as living in the household of William Peirce." data-id="chron11"> <span class="date" id="chron11">January 24, 1625 </span><div class="chrondescription">The Jamestown muster lists "Angelo a Negro Woman" as living in the household of William Peirce.</div></div></div></div> <!--    Further Reading--><div class="furtherreadingw wrapper" id="furtherreading"><div class="furtherreading"><div class="label">FURTHER READING</div><div class="div"><ul><li>Heywood, Linda M. and John K. Thornton. <em>Central Africans, Atlantic Creoles, and the Foundation of the Americas, 1585–1660.</em> Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, 2007.</li><li>McCartney, Martha W. <em>Virginia Immigrants and Adventurers, 1607–1635.</em> Baltimore, Maryland: Genealogical Publishing Company, 2007.</li></ul></div></div></div> <!--    Citations--><div class="citationw wrapper"><div class="citation"><div class="label">CITE THIS ENTRY</div><dl><dt>APA Citation:</dt><dd>Wolfe, Brendan. Angela (fl. 1619–1625). (2020, December 07). In <em>Encyclopedia Virginia.</em> https://encyclopediavirginia.org/entries/angela-fl-1619-1625.</dd><dt>MLA Citation:</dt><dd>Wolfe, Brendan. "Angela (fl. 1619–1625)" <em>Encyclopedia Virginia.</em> Virginia Humanities, (07 Dec. 2020). Web. 27 Apr. 2024</dd></dl> <small style="margin-left: 1em;"><em>Last updated: 2024, February 09</em></small></div></div> <!--    Author/Contributor--> <!-- Feedback --><div class="feedbackw wrapper"> <details class="feedbackform"> <summary>Feedback</summary> <div class='gf_browser_chrome gform_wrapper gform_legacy_markup_wrapper gform-theme--no-framework' data-form-theme='legacy' data-form-index='0' id='gform_wrapper_1' ><form method='post' enctype='multipart/form-data'  id='gform_1'  action='/entries/angela-fl-1619-1625/?utm_source=feedburner&#038;utm_medium=feed&#038;utm_campaign=Feed%3A+encyclopediavirginia%2Fcat32+%28Encyclopedia+Virginia%3A+Colonial+History+%28ca.+1560%E2%80%931763%29%29' data-formid='1' novalidate><div class='gform-body gform_body'><ul id='gform_fields_1' class='gform_fields top_label form_sublabel_below description_below'><li id="field_1_4" class="gfield gfield--type-hidden gform_hidden field_sublabel_below gfield--no-description field_description_below gfi